When to Use Different MCP Servers
For a first-time no-code developer, here's a guide on when to use each of the MCP servers you've installed:
Sequential Thinking

Use when you need to break down complex problems into smaller, manageable steps
Ideal for planning your project structure before implementation
Helpful when you're stuck and need to work through a problem methodically
Great for documenting your thought process for future reference

GitHub

Use for version control and storing your project code
When collaborating with others on the same project
When you need to track changes to your code over time
For backing up your project safely
When you want to share your code with others or contribute to open source

Brave Search

Use when researching solutions to specific problems
When looking for code examples or tutorials
For finding libraries or tools that might help with your project
When you need to understand concepts or technical terms
For discovering best practices in your area of development

Supabase MCP Server

Use when you need a database for your project
When you want to store and retrieve user data
For implementing authentication features
When you need real-time data functionality
For API development without writing backend code
When you need to store files or media

Puppeteer

Use for web scraping when you need to collect data from websites
For automating browser-based tasks
When testing web applications
For generating screenshots or PDFs of web pages
When you need to interact with websites programmatically
For creating bots that can navigate and interact with web interfaces

Would you like more specific guidance on how to get started with any of these tools?